				content: "Viz., by examining whether their teaching be agreeable to the rule of the Catholic faith, and the doctrine of the church. For as he says, (ver. 6,) <i>He that knoweth God, heareth us</i> [the pastors of the church]. <i>By this we know the spirit of truth, and the spirit of error.</i>"
			},
					5519: {
				id_comment: 5519,
				source_str: 'Every spirit which confesseth',
				caption: 'Every spirit which confesseth, &c.',
				content: "Not that the confession of this point of faith alone, is, at all times, and in all cases, sufficient; but that with relation to that time, and for that part of the Christian doctrine, which was then particularly to be confessed, taught, and maintained against the heretics of those days, this was the most proper token, by which the true teachers might be distinguished from the false."
			},
					5520: {
				id_comment: 5520,
				source_str: 'that dissolveth Jesus',
				caption: 'That dissolveth Jesus.',
				content: "Viz., either by denying his humanity, or his divinity."
			},
					5521: {
				id_comment: 5521,
				source_str: 'he is now already in the world',
				caption: 'He is now already in the world.',
				content: "Not in his person, but in his spirit, and in his precursors."
			},
					5522: {
				id_comment: 5522,
				source_str: 'Fear is not in charity',
				caption: 'Fear is not in charity, &c.',
				content: "Perfect charity, or love, banisheth <i>human fear,</i> that is, the fear of men; as also all <i>perplexing fear,</i> which makes men mistrust or despair of Godâs mercy; and that kind of <i>servile fear,</i> which makes them fear the punishment of sin more than the offence offered to God. But it no way excludes the wholesome <i>fear of Godâs judgments,</i> so often recomended in holy writ; nor that <i>fear and trembling,</i> with which we are told to work out our salvation. Phil. 2. 12."
			},
			};
